msContents.summary: History of Kashmir and surrounding areas. Begins with a eulogy on Lord William Cavendish Bentick and is dedicated to William Augustus Brooke of the East India Company, whose title was Ḥishmat al-Dawlah. There is a preface by the author in which he relates how he met Brooke and where he was sent on missions. He also mentions that this book is largely based on an earlier history of Kashmir, "Gawhār-i tuḥfah-ʼi ʻĀlim Shāhī" by Muḥammad Badīʻ al-Dīn Abū al-Qāsim Aslam and on meetings with, and a book by Sayyid Ghulām-Ḥusayn Khān. The work is divided into four chapters: 1. Kashmir, 2. Tibet and Kalmakistan including an account of Mānī, the painter, and founder of Manicheism, 3. Badakhshan and 4. highlands of Afghanistan

عبد القادر خان ابن واصل على خان،

author.name: Free Library of Philadelphia. Rare Book Department. John Frederick Lewis Collection of Oriental Manuscripts

supportDesc.extent: 189 foliated leaves : 269 x 168 (175 x 85) mm bound to 271 x 172 mm
supportDesc.foliation: Contemporary foliation in ink in Hindu-Arabic numerals, upper left recto; catchwords every verso, lower left.

scriptDesc.scriptNote: Written in nastaʻlīq in black ink; pointed.

decoDesc.decoNote: Illuminated headpiece in gold and blue with text on cloudbands with gold fill with one section of 4 lines written on gold background (f. 1v-2r); final opening also written on cloudbands with gold fill (f. 188v-189r). Border-ruled in gold, red, blue with a page-opening frame rule in blue. Rubrications in red

binding.p: Mottled leather over pulpboard with gold tooled frame; black leather doublure; blue painted edges.

origin.p: The item was copied in Muḥammadʹābād, Banāras in 1245 AH, 1830 CE (f. 189r); the scribe is not named, but is likely the same as the author.

history.provenance: Formerly owned by John Frederick Lewis (bookplate inside back cover).
